text: Genome Mining-Directed Activation of a Silent Angucycline Biosynthetic Gene Cluster in Streptomyces chattanoogensis Zhenxing Zhou,[a] Qingqing Xu,[a] Qingting Bu,[a] Yuanyang Guo,[a] Shuiping Liu,[a] Yu Liu,[b] Yiling Du,[a, d] and Yongquan Li*[a, c] Genomic sequencing of actinomycetes has revealed the pres- ence of numerous gene clusters seemingly capable of natural product biosynthesis, yet most clusters are cryptic under lab- oratory conditions. Bioinformatics analysis of the completely sequenced genome of Streptomyces chattanoogensis L10 (CGMCC 2644) revealed a silent angucycline biosynthetic gene cluster. The overexpression of a pathway-specific activator gene under the constitutive ermE* promoter successfully trig- Filamentous Gram-positive bacteria of the genus Streptomyces are prolific producers of various bioactive molecules, such as antibiotics, In recent years, numerous secondary metabolism gene clusters have been uncovered through Streptomyces genome sequenc- ing,[2] indicating that streptomycetes are important reservoirs of natural products. However, many biosynthetic gene clusters are silent under laboratory growth conditions, presenting a po- tential bottleneck for new natural product discovery. Several approaches have been proposed to detect the products of such silent gene clusters in Streptomyces, including ribosome engineering,[3] heterologous expression of an entire gene clus- ter,[4] metabolism remodeling,[5] and deletion or overexpression of regulatory genes.[6] Streptomyces chattanoogensis L10 (CGMCC 2644) is an indus- trial producer of natamycin, which has been widely used as anti-mold preservative.[7] Bioinformatics analyses of the com- ChemBioChem 0000, 00, 0 – 0 These are not the final page numbers! Two novel members of the angucycline antibiotic family, chat- tamycins A and B, were further isolated and elucidated. Biolog- ical activity assays demonstrated that chattamycin B possesses good antitumor activities against human cancer cell lines and moderate antibacterial activities. The results presented here provide a feasible method to activate silent angucycline bio- synthetic gene clusters to discover potential new drug leads. pletely sequenced S. chattanoogensis L10 chromosome uncov- ered 34 putative secondary metabolic pathways, including twelve polyketide synthetase (PKS) gene clusters (unpublished data). Natamycin is directed by a type I PKS gene cluster cover- ing 20 open reading frames (orf7600–orf7619).[8] However, the metabolic products of other clusters remain unknown, except one which has been identified as migrastatin.[9]

We have focused our attention on a silent gene cluster that is putatively responsible for the biosynthesis of angucycline- like antibiotics in S. chattanoogensis L10. Angucyclines are type II PKS-decaketide-derived natural products. They are of particular interest because of their richness in chemical scaf- folds and various biological activities, predominantly anticancer and antibacterial activities.[10] In this work, the constitutive ex- pression of the gene chaI, encoding a putative pathway-specif- ic activator, successfully triggered the expression of the chatta- mycin biosynthetic gene cluster (cha), which was not ex- pressed under our laboratory conditions. Two angucycline anti- biotics, chattamycins A and B, were isolated and identified. Chattamycin B was shown to have an obvious inhibitory effect on the growth of human cancer cell lines and bacteria. In silico analysis of the chattamycin gene cluster For our genomics-based discovery of natural products and their biosynthetic mechanisms, we focused our attention on the putative silent angucycline biosynthetic gene cluster cha. DNA analysis of a 42.2 kb cluster revealed the presence of 36 genes (Figure 1) that might be responsible for the biosynthesis of angucycline-like antibiotics (Table 1). to SaqGT5 of Micromonospora sp. Tu6368. SaqGT5 is a d-olivo- syltransferase that forms a C–C glycosidic linkage.[15] ChaGT4 is probably involved in l-rhodinose attachment due to its 81 % identity to LndGT4 of Streptomyces globisporus.[16] ChaGT5 (53 % identity to SaqGT3) and ChaGT6 (56 % identity to SaqGT6) are probably responsible for attachment of d-olivose and l-2-deoxyfucose,[15] respectively. Ten more genes are pre- dicted to be involved in the formation of deoxy-hexoses, which are the substrates of the six glycotransferases. Activation of the silent chattamycin biosynthetic cluster In silico analysis of the cha gene cluster identified three genes encoding potential pathway-specific regulators. Both ChaK and ChaK1 belong to the TetR family of transcriptional regulators. ChaK is highly homologous to LanK, which is a repressor of the landomycin A biosynthetic pathway.[17] The deduced amino acid sequence of ChaK1 is very similar to the gamma-butyro- lactone (GBL) receptor protein. The gene chaI encodes a pro- tein that is an angucyclic regulator.[18] This kind of protein has a C-terminal winged-helix DNA-binding domain and an N-ter- minal signal receiver domain. ChaI shows high identity to other positive regulators of angucycline biosynthesis, such as JadR1 (48.9 % identity to ChaI) of Streptomyces veneuelae[19] and LanI (47.4 % identity to ChaI) of Streptomyces cyanogenus S136,[20] indicating that ChaI might also be an activator.

To examine the function of ChaI and to activate the silent chattamycin gene cluster, the chaI gene was cloned into the integrative vector pLM1 under the control of the constitutive ermE* promoter.[21] The resultant plasmid pLZ9 was integrated into the chromosome of S. chattanoogensis L10 to create the strain S. chattanoogensis ZJUX3 (L10/chaIOE). S. chattanoogensis L10 harboring an empty pLM1 vector (L10/pLM1) was used as a negative control. Next, we examined whether the genomic copy of selected genes (chaA on behalf of the minimal PKS genes; chaM on behalf of the post-PKS genes; chaS on behalf of the deoxy-hexose biosynthetic genes; chaGT1 on behalf of the glycosyltransferase genes) in the chattamycin gene cluster were being transcribed by overexpressing chaI. Transcription of the principal sigma gene hrdB was used as a positive con- trol. the selected genes were poorly or not expressed in the control strain L10/pLM1 (Figure 2), although the chaI gene was not completely silent. From the organization of the chattamycin gene cluster, chaA, chaM, and chaS seemed to be located at the same operon. Therefore, lack of expression of the above three genes likely in- dicated that the PKS genes, the post-PKS tailoring genes, and some deoxy-hexose biosynthetic genes were not transcribed in L10/pLM1. In contrast, the selected genes were highly ex- pressed in the L10/chaIOE strain, suggesting that ChaI is a pos- sible pathway-specific activator for chattamycin biosynthesis. ure 3 C). Next, scale-up fermentation was carried out. Two com- pounds, chattamycins A and B (Scheme 1), were isolated from the extracts of the L10/chaIOE strain grown in SG medium for 72 h. Their structures were eluci- dated by mass spectrometry (MS) and one- and two-dimen- sional NMR. The HPLC-ESI-MS of chattamy- cin A displayed a mass of m/z 708.2 [M+NH4] + in positive-ion mode and a mass of m/z 689.1 [M(cid:2)H](cid:2) in negative ion mode, suggesting a molecular mass of 690 Da. The formula for chatta- mycin A was as C34H42O15, which was further con- firmed high-resolution (HR)ESI-MS and NMR spectra. The 1H NMR of chattamycin A (Table S1 in the Supporting Infor- mation) showed one signal at d = 12.37 ppm, the presence of a phenol. Two aro- matic protons at d = 7.81 ppm and d = 7.54 ppm with an ortho coupling constant of 7.79 Hz and d = an 5.44 ppm were found. In the 13C NMR spectrum, a typical qui- (d = 189.1, none 184.5 ppm) was identified, and the small shift difference of Dd = 4.6 ppm indicated the existence of flanking hydroxy groups in close proximity.[22] COSY and HMBC NMR experiments con- firmed the angucycline skeleton and of a methyl group to C3 and an acetoxy group to C5 (Figure 4 A). The relative stereochemistry of the angucycline core was de- duced by ROESY experiments (Figure 4 B). A strong ROESY con- tact between H-5 and OH-6 indicated their cis arrangement. The orientation of ring A relative to ring B was deduced by ob- serving two other ROESY correlations (from H-5 to Ha-4 and from OH-4a to Hb-4). A strong ROESY signal between H-1 and OH-12B was also observed. All key ROESY contacts were fur- ther verified by ChemDraw 3D MM2 minimized energy model (Figure 5). Therefore, the relative stereochemistry of the angu- cycline core was revealed as shown in Scheme 1. Notably, the stereochemistry at C1 and C6 in chattamycin A is opposite to the stereochemistry in warkmycin[23] and P371A1.[24] In the sugar region, the 13C NMR spectrum of chattamycin A showed an acetal carbon signal (d = 98.0 ppm) and two methyl group signals indicating two deoxy sugars, termed sugars A and B, one of which is C-glycosidically linked. The substituents of sugar A were determined by COSY, HSQC, and HMBC correlations. In addition, as H-1A of sugar A (cid:2) 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. showed a broad singlet in the 1H NMR spectrum, it was not possible to determine the exact coupling constant of H-1A. Be- cause of the peak width (6.76 Hz) at the half-height of H-1A, an axial–axial coupling of H-1A with H-2A was excluded. Three ROESY contacts between H-3A and Ha-2A, between H-3A and He-2A, and between H-4A and H-5A revealed an axial orienta- tion of the methyl and methoxy groups. Comparison of our findings with literature revealed that sugar A is a a-l-3-5-diepi- oleandrose. The attachment of sugar A to the angucycline core was established by a 3JC-H long-range coupling between H-1A and C-1, as well as between C-1A and H-1. The coupling constant of H-1B (J = 11.53 Hz) indicated an axial orientation of H-1B. Three ROESY contacts between H-1B and H-3B, between H-1B and H-5B and between H-4B and H- 6B revealed that the hydroxy group at C-4B and the methyl group of C6 are equatorial. The attachment of sugar B to the angucycline core was established by 3JC-H long-range coupling between H-10 and C-1B. Therefore, our results determined the constitution of sugar B as a b-d-olivose bound to C9 of the angucycline core.

The formula of chattamycin B, with a molecular mass of 1094 Da, was established as C53H74O24 according to HRESI-MS and NMR spectra. As chattamycins A and B show closely similar UV and visible spectra, they must have same angucycline core. 1H and 13C NMR data for chattamycin B showed high similarity in the signal regions of the angucycline core and sugar A to those of chattamycin A. Three more anomeric carbons (d = 96.4, 99.9, 92.6 ppm) and anomeric protons (d = 4.71, 4.63, 4.98 ppm) were also observed, suggesting three more sugars, termed sugars C, D, and E in chattamycin B. A Dd (7.1 ppm) of C-3B in chattamycin A (d = 71.5 ppm) compared to chatta- mycin B (d = 78.6 ppm) indicated a glycosidic linkage from sugar C to sugar B, which was further certified by an HMBC correlation from H-3B to C-1C. The substituents of sugar C were determined by COSY, HSQC, and HMBC correlations. The coupling constant of H-1C (J = 9.59 Hz) revealed an axial orientation of H-1C. Two ROESY contacts (between H-1C and H-3C, and between H-4C and H- 6C) and the coupling constant of H-3C (J = 8.70 Hz) identified sugar C as b-d-olivose. Furthermore, ROESY correlations be- tween H-1C and H-3B verified a glycosidic linkage from sugar C to sugar B. ChemBioChem 0000, 00, 0 – 0 These are not the final page numbers! Sugars D and E were established as b-d-olivose and a-l-3- respectively, by 2D NMR experiments. methoxy-rhodinose, HMBC correlations (from H-4C to C-1D and from H-1D to C-4C) and the coupling constant of H-1D (J = 10.0 Hz) demonstrated a b-glycosidic linkage from sugar D to sugar C. Similarly, sugar E showed an a-glycosidic bond to sugar D, due to HMBC contact (from H-3D to C-1E) and the small coupling constant (J = 2.82 Hz) of H-1E. Two ROESY signals (between H-4C and H- 1D, and between H-3D and H-1E) provided further evidence of glycosidic linkages from sugar D to sugar C and from sugar E to sugar D. The structures of chattamycins A and B resemble those of warkmycin and P371A1. However, these angucyclines are dif- ferent in the substituents on the sugar units. In chattamycin B, a tetrasaccharide chain composed of b-olivose-(3!1)-b-oli- vose-(4!1)-b-olivose-(3!1)-a-3-methoxy-rhodinose was at- tached to C9. In warkmycin and P371A1, C9 was glycosylated with three sugar moieties. Therefore, chattamycins A and B are two novel members of the angucycline antibiotics family. Bioactivity of the chattamycins

The broad range of bioactivities of angucyclines, predominant- ly antitumor and antibacterial activities, prompted us to inves- tigate the biological activity of the chattamycins. Chattamy- cins A and B were assessed for their activities against human lines MCF-7 breast cancer and human HepG2 hepatoma cell (Table S2). Cell viability assays demonstrated that chattamy- (IC50 = 1.08 (cid:3) cin B was more active against MCF-7 cells 0.09 mm) than against HepG2 cells (IC50 = 5.93 (cid:3) 0.10 mm). In both MCF-7 and HepG2 cells, chattamycin A was less active (IC50 = 6.46 (cid:3) 0.49 mm and IC50 > 10 mm, respectively). These re- sults were consistent with previous reports that angucyclines with shorter saccharide moieties were less active against tumor cells[25] and indicated that chattamycin B is a promising new lead for anticancer drug discovery. Furthermore, antibacterial activities of chattamycins were also investigated against three bacteria (Table S2). Both chatta- mycins A and B were weakly active against Escherichia coli K12 and Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 25923. Meanwhile, chatta- mycin B showed moderate activity (IC50 = 102.59 (cid:3) 5.85 mm) against Bacillus subtilis ATCC 67736.

In this study, we successfully activated a cryptic angucycline biosynthetic gene cluster by overexpressing a putative path- way-specific activator in S. chattanoogensis L10. Two novel an- gucycline antibiotics with good antitumor activities against human cancer cell lines and weak antibacterial activities were isolated and their structures elucidated. To our knowledge, be- sides chattamycins, only two more angucyclines, P371A1/ P371A2 and warkmycin, have an acetoxy group at C5. Mean- while, the chattamycins have stereochemical specificities at C1 and C6. Therefore, further functional elucidation of the en- zymes responsible for the above characteristics of chattamy- cins will deepen our understanding of the formation processes (cid:2) 0000 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim of angucyclines. As ChaI-like regulators are highly conserved, it is a feasible strategy to awaken the silent angucycline gene clusters by overexpressing the pathway-specific activators, which is an easy and time-effective approach. Bacterial strains, plasmids, and culture conditions: Bacterial strains and plasmids used in this study are listed in Table S3. S. chattanoogensis strains were grown on YMG solid medium for spore preparation and were grown in trypticase soy broth (3 %, w/ v) for the preparation of genomic DNA.[7] E. coli strains were main- tained on lysogeny broth (LB) agar and grown in LB liquid medium containing appropriate antibiotics as needed. E. coli–Streptomyces conjugation was carried out according to standard protocol.[26]

Construction of the mutant strain: All primers used in this study are listed in Table S4. The chaA gene deletion mutant was con- structed by the l RED-based PCR-targeting system.[26] The aac(3)IV cassette from pHY773 was amplified by PCR using oligonucleotide primers pkbKS-de-F and pkbKS-de-R. The gel-purified PCR frag- ments were electroporated into E. coli BW25113 containing the plasmid pIJ790 and the S. chattanoogensis L10 cosmid SCH23F9. Positive transformants were selected by restriction enzyme (XhoI) digestion of the PCR products using the primer pair chaA-ver-F and chaA-ver-R. The mutant cosmid was transformed into the non- methylating E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 strain, and the strain was then conjugated with S. chattanoogensis L10. The exconjugants were selected by using apramycin (50 mg mL(cid:2)1) and nalidixic acid (25 mg mL(cid:2)1). Double crossover mutants were selected for their apramycin resistance and thiostrepton sensitivity. The chaA mutant was named S. chattanoogensis ZJUD36. Overexpression of the pathway-specific regulator: The chaI gene was amplified by PCR from S. chattanoogensis L10 genomic DNA with the primers chaI-OE-F and chaI-OE-R. The PCR product was cloned into pTA2 (Toyobo), and the integrity of the insert was con- firmed by sequencing. After restriction digestion with NdeI and NotI, the insert was cloned into the pLM1[27] vector under the con- trol of the ermE* promoter. The resulting recombinant plasmid, pLZ9, was introduced into S. chattanoogensis L10 by conjugation from E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002. The mutant strain was named S. chattanoogensis ZJUX3. S. chattanoogensis L10 harboring empty plasmid pLM1 was used as a negative control.

For overexpression of the pathway-specific regulator in S. chatta- noogensis DchaA, the chaI gene was cloned into pIJ8662 (a deriva- tive plasmid of pLM1), resulting in the recombinant plasmid pLZ10. Next, the plasmid pLZ10 was introduced into S. chattanoogensis ZJUD36 (DchaA) by conjugation from E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002. The mutant strain was named S. chattanoogensis ZJUX5. Transcriptional analysis: Total RNA of S. chattanoogensis mutant strains was isolated from SG medium culture. Genomic DNA con- tamination was diminished by RNase-free DNaseI (Takara). RNA was transcribed to cDNA by reverse transcriptase M-MLV (RNase H(cid:2), Takara), according to the manufacturer’s protocol. The cDNA was amplified with rTaq (Takara), according to the following conditions: 2 min at 94 8C; 30 cycles of 30 s at 94 8C, 30 s at 55 8C, and 45 s at 72 8C; one extension of 5 min at 72 8C. The transcription of hrdB, which encodes the principal sigma factor of RNA polymerase, was used as the positive control. Structure elucidation: ESI-MS was recorded on an Agilent 6460 triple quadrupole mass spectrometer coupled to an Agilent 1290 ChemBioChem 0000, 00, 0 – 0 HPLC system, and HRESI-MS was recorded on an AB Sciex 5600 Q- TOF system. 1H and 13C (DEPT-135) NMR spectroscopy, 1H,1H COSY, ROESY, HSQC, and HMBC NMR spectra were performed on a Bruker Advance 600 spectrometer. [D6]DMSO was used as a solvent for NMR experiments, and chemical shifts were referenced to the sol- vent peaks.

Fermentation and isolation of chattamycins A and B: S. chatta- noogensis strains were grown on YMG agar plates. After incubation for five days at 30 8C, small areas of well-developed mycelium cut was used to incubate one 250 cm3 Erlenmeyer flask containing SG medium (35 mL).[28] The flask was incubated at 200 rpm and 30 8C for 36 h. The obtained pre-culture (35 mL) was used to incubate four 500 cm3 flasks (each with 2 mL of pre-culture) containing SG medium (100 mL). This second feed culture was incubated at 200 rpm and 30 8C for two days and was then transferred into a 15 L stirred tank fermenter containing SG medium (8 L). Fermen- tation was carried out at 30 8C for three days with an air-flow rate of one volume per volume per minute and an agitation speed of 200 rpm.

The fermentation broth was harvested by centrifugation at 4500 g for 15 min. The resulting mycelial cake was extracted three times with acetone; the water phase was extracted with three volumes of ethyl acetate. Both extracts were combined and evaporated to dryness under vacuum at 45 8C; this afforded 9.0 g of dark reddish powder. The crude extract was dissolved in methanol (80 mL) and purified by a Lumtech semi-preparative HPLC apparatus (column: Kromasil C18, 5 mm, ø10 (cid:3) 250 mm; eluent: H2O/acetonitrile, isocrat- ic gradient: 32 % acetonitrile, flow rate: 4 mL min(cid:2)1) to yield frac- tion I (eluted time: 6.4–7.0 min) and fraction II (eluted time: 14.0– 15.2 min). The two fractions were further purified on an Agi- lent 1260 HPLC apparatus fitted with an Eclipse Plus C18 column (5 mm, Ø 4.6 (cid:3) 250 mm). Chattamycin A was purified from fraction I with an isocratic gradient of 26 % (v/v) acetonitrile, and chattamy- cin B was purified from fraction II with an isocratic gradient of 31 % (v/v) acetonitrile. After concentration in vacuo to dryness, chatta- mycin A was obtained as a yellow powder in a yield of 6.0 mg and chattamycin B as a yellow powder with a yield of 10.0 mg.

For comparison of metabolism profiles, the crude extracts of L10/ chaIOE, DchaA/chaIOE and L10/pLM1 (20 mL) were injected into an Agilent 1260 HPLC system fitted with an Eclipse Plus C18 column (5 mm, ø 4.6 (cid:3) 250 mm).
